Really?  Has Microsoft ever put out products at the pace and quality that
Intel does?  For example, the PCI bus was designed by Intel, released
royalty free and standardized, and is now not only the major bus on PCs,
but also on new Macs, and many workstations.  It's a very well designed
bus, and that's why it has been so quickly (its only 18 months old) and
widely adopted.

While the original x86 architecture was certainly not as clean as, say
the 68000, (due mainly to the desire to be able to run old 8051 code)
Intel has done an excellent job of keeping x86 performance comparable to
the best microprocessors available at any time.  Ever check out the
current performance of x86 processors vs. 68000 series ones?  Microsoft,
on the other hand, consistently turns out software that is quite slow
and late.  It's absurd that 10 years after the 386 was released Microsoft
still hasn't moved its user base up to a 32-bit operating system
(neglecting the small minority with NT).

Finally, look at core logic chip sets.  Intel got into core logic a few
years ago, and now releases the best core logic chip sets for PCs.  The
Triton chip set is the best performing PC chip set, and other core logic
vendors are scrambling to get out chips that match its support for
EDO DRAM, pipelined, synchronous second level cache, and bus mastering
EIDE.

