YOU don't know what you're talking about.  Here are the performance
figures (from http://infopad.eecs.berkeley.edu/CIC/summary/summary.html).
Each chip in the table below is rated at the fastest clock speed
currently available (note that the P6 is currently only available to OEMs,
although systems built around it will ship soon).


Chip                        SpecInt               Specfp
------------------------------------------------------------------------
Pentium (133 MHz)           155                   116

PowerPC 601+ (100 MHz)      105                   125

PowerPC 604 (133 MHz)       176.4                 156.5
(in an R6000 workstation)

P6 (133 MHz)                >200                  Not disclosed yet.


Instead of being "far inferior" to PPC 601s, the fastest Pentiums have
48% better integer performance, at the price of 7% inferior floating
point performance.  The PowerPC 604 is faster than the fastest Pentium,
but the P6 is faster than it.  The x86 and PPC architectures are staying
fairly close in performance

